{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510657"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11639"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11639"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.08,0.01,0.42,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4265"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94583"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"926"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26976"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46197"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a head-on motor vehicle crash in which he was a restrained front seat passenger. He has been given one litre of isotonic saline by the retrieval team on the way to hospital. He complains of left upper quadrant pain. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell with pulse rate 112/min, blood pressure 98/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.4\u00b0C. He has tenderness in the left upper quadrant with localised rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal haemoglobin 94 g/L (130-180) and lactate 1.8 mmol/L (0.5-2.2). A CT scan is performed (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home with outpatient follow-up","Admit for observation","Red cell scan","Splenic artery embolisation","Splenectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man has a grade V splenic injury as per AAST grading system. As this is a high-grade injury of the spleen involving vascular injury, and he is on the borderline of haemodynamic stability, some form of active intervention is required. He is still hyptotensive despite administration of intravenous fluid. If this was a grade IV injury, the most appropriate management would be \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic artery embolisation \u003C/strong\u003Eto preserve splenic parenchyma. However, the CT scan shows a shattered spleen and any attempt at splenic conservation is most likely to be fruitless and put the patient at risk of going into hypovolaemic shock. At the moment he is on the brink of haemodyamic collapse. He will require surgical intervention and splenectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home with review the following day\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmitting to the ward for further observation\u003C/strong\u003E are inappropriate given this degree of splenic injury. \u003Cstrong\u003ERed cell scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not required here as the contrast CT has revealed the degree of splenic injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Ctbody\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrade\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInjury Description\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubcapsular haematoma \u0026lt;10% surface area; capsular tear \u0026lt;1 cm depth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-operative management\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EII (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hUOQmHCc3aIu2O52Ix1ScO5C0S5LPc.jpg\u0022\u003Eimage\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubcapsular haematoma 10-50% surface area; intraparenchymal haematoma \u0026lt;5 cm; laceration 1-3 cm depth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-operative management\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIII (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/etDgNVqn11HnjaoWFNNaIv99gdmzNe.jpg\u0022\u003Eimage\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubcapsular haematoma \u0026gt;50% surface area or expanding; intraparenchymal haematoma \u22655 cm; laceration \u0026gt;3 cm depth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-operative management or embolisation if stable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIV (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8TxOSLyiL67M8Gungfgm0yhMb7E4Mr.jpg\u0022\u003Eimage\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaceration involving segmental or hilar vessels with major devascularisation (\u0026gt;25% of spleen)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmbolisation if stable; splenectomy if unstable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EV (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jkjWf1S5dL5LnUnKZC0LlVcSDdkPPK.jpg\u0022\u003Eimage\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShattered spleen; hilar vascular injury with devascularised spleen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmbolisation if stable; splenectomy if unstable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/tbody\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-operative management is preferred for haemodynamically stable patients with low-grade splenic injuries.","Grade V splenic injuries require immediate splenectomy regardless of haemodynamic status.","The American Association for the Surgery of Trauma grading system guides management decisions for splenic trauma."],"references":["El-Matbouly M, Jabbour G, El-Menyar A, Peralta R, Abdelrahman H, Zarour A, Al-Hassani A, Al-Thani H. Blunt splenic trauma: Assessment, management and outcomes. Surgeon. 2016 Feb;14(1):52-8. doi: 10.1016/j.surge.2015.08.001. Epub 2015 Aug 30. PMID: 26330367. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26330367/","Coccolini F, Montori G, Catena F, Kluger Y, Biffl W, Moore EE, Reva V, Bing C, Bala M, Fugazzola P, Bahouth H, Marzi I, Velmahos G, Ivatury R, Soreide K, Horer T, Ten Broek R, Pereira BM, Fraga GP, Inaba K, Kashuk J, Parry N, Masiakos PT, Mylonas KS, Kirkpatrick A, Abu-Zidan F, Gomes CA, Benatti SV, Naidoo N, Salvetti F, Maccatrozzo S, Agnoletti V, Gamberini E, Solaini L, Costanzo A, Celotti A, Tomasoni M, Khokha V, Arvieux C, Napolitano L, Handolin L, Pisano M, Magnone S, Spain DA, de Moya M, Davis KA, De Angelis N, Leppaniemi A, Ferrada P, Latifi R, Navarro DC, Otomo Y, Coimbra R, Maier RV, Moore F, Rizoli S, Sakakushev B, Galante JM, Chiara O, Cimbanassi S, Mefire AC, Weber D, Ceresoli M, Peitzman AB, Wehlie L, Sartelli M, Di Saverio S, Ansaloni L. Splenic trauma: WSES classification and guidelines for adult and pediatric patients. World J Emerg Surg. 2017 Aug 18;12:40. doi: 10.1186/s13017-017-0151-4. PMID: 28828034; PMCID: PMC5562999. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28828034/","Bodansky D, Jones R, Tucker ON. An alternative option in the management of blunt splenic injury. J Surg Case Rep. 2013 Aug 14;2013(8):rjt061. doi: 10.1093/jscr/rjt061. PMID: 24964468; PMCID: PMC3813711. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24964468/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11639"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20102"},{"type":"media","id":"20103"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22085"},{"type":"media","id":"22086"},{"type":"media","id":"22087"},{"type":"media","id":"22088"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20102"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/df7bf01c-424a-441c-928a-dd202151c62b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/df7bf01c-424a-441c-928a-dd202151c62b.jpg","isProcessed":t